The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

 Memon aide held guilty

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Mumbai, Sept. 27: A Tiger Memon associate was today found guilty of planting explosives at a five-star hotel and a congested market during the 1993 Bombay blasts that killed 257 people and injured 713.

 Mohammad Mushtaq Musa Tarani has been convicted of attending a conspiracy meeting called by prime accused Memon, being part of a reconnaissance mission to survey terror targets and planting RDX in a suitcase at Hotel Juhu Centaur and in a scooter in Zaveri Bazaar.

 Special Tada court judge Pramod Kode accepted Taranis confession detailing his role in the plot and the testimony of two witnesses at the hotel and one in the market.

 He found Tarani guilty of all principal charges against him criminal conspiracy and aiding, abetting and knowingly committing a terrorist act resulting in injuries.

 Tarani was also convicted of charges of attempt to murder, causing hurt and damage to property, and under the explosives act.

 He could face punishment ranging from five years in jail to life imprisonment.




